text: I don't know about Peter Pan's origins, but Hook being a good guy at first, is a little confusing, more so because Disney has those Tinker Bell films, which are set *before* Disney's Peter Pan film, one of which, The Pirate Fairy, also had a young Hook, but Peter wasn't around. I know these films are based off the Peter Pan book, but I can't help but think of Disney's Peter Pan animated film, when all these prequels start showing up.  Makes me wonder what makes Hook turn here. At least in The Pirate Fairy, Hook was still a pirate, and he wasn't good there. Here however, they have stuff about a prophesy, so even if Hook is good here, his fate cannot be changed, no doubt they're going to hint at Hook losing his hand, and becoming the captain. I know that all the fairy tales Disney made films off of, were actually pretty damn dark, so I'm assuming this film follows the book more.

text: Be mad about the fact that an actress with darker skin wasn't cast, but don't try to say Joe Wright is trying to pass Rooney Mara off as a Native American. He's specifically taken the Native American tribe and instead made it a combination of numerous native cultures from all over the world. So in his Neverland, Tiger Lily is something else. What else? We don't know. We don't know yet where she came from. But this isn't "redface", nor is it whitewashing.  Here's what I'm excited about: Instead of being absolutely silent or completely missing from the storyline, like most versions of Peter Pan I've seen (or omg this awful high school production that made her talk in this awfully racist vernacular and she was all lusty and clingy with Peter, it was disgusting).....in Wright's version, she not only speaks, she's a leader. She's a warrior. She gets to fight Blackbeard in the rigging of a ship. She isn't a damsel in distress. She's protecting her people. THAT IS WHAT I'M EXCITED ABOUT. The color of her skin makes no damn difference, because Tiger Lily actually gets to DO THINGS.

text: Why is every simple fairy tale turned into a "PROPHECY" movie nowadays? Tim Burton did this with 'Wonderland' too. These movies are so intolerable, because they ruin the simplicity and charm of the tale they try to tell. Look at all this nonsense about "uniting" against the pirates, and Peter Pan being some chosen warrior.  What happened to the simple allegory of perpetual boyhood that truly was 'Peter Pan'? Nothing will ever touch P.J Hogan's 2003 adaptation of this story. Even though he took his own liberties, he stayed faithful to the spirit of the work.

text: Funny how legends like Captain Hook start out as completely innocent, fun-loving, sweet, nice, pleasant, and loveable good people, but then something bad or tramautic happens to them which changes them and how they think of everything, forever. Just think of Anakin Skywalker from the first Star Wars movies or Lex Luthor or Doctor Doom. Lex Luthor was actually pretty happy and good before Superman came to Earth, of course it's different in the comics, Lex Luthor blames Superman for a failed weapons test where Lex Luthor gets all his hair burned off, but I digress. Doctor Doom just wants what's best for his people in Latveria. Anybody else know any other people who fit into this category? I just remembered, Harvey Dent from The Dark Knight. I think some real life people share similar life stories to these fantasy characters.

text: For those who are confused, I would like to explain why Tiger Lily is white:¬† They're trying to sell the typical "white person goes to save all the stupid natives who are too dumb to save themselves!" b.s. story, right down to how he's praised as "The chosen one!".¬† The problem is that if they left Tiger Lily as native, it would make it too obvious. ¬† So instead of just not feeding us the same b.s. "white savior!" movie again, they just got rid of the brown support character (lol).¬† Easy Hollywood fix, right? Why bother making an interesting movie, when you can just regurgitate the same old b.s. and simply get rid of the dark-skin characters.¬† Hahah!  That's about as clever as it seems to get.¬† The costumes and sets look very cheap, like "high school play" cheap, mixed with good CGI, that's why the trailer seem odd.¬† The actress playing Tiger Lily seems uncomfortable in the role, almost like she doesn't want to be there (maybe she just saw the role as a paycheck?).¬† The camera angles are also very awkward during some scenes, like it's a film student's first try-hard project. Also, captain hook as the good guy? Ok, whatever.. I'm done.  This movie is an outright disaster on many levels.¬† You won't catch it at first, but watch the trailer a couple of times and you'll see what I'm talking about.

text: Looks ok, but just the word "prophecy" god they are in every fantasy/scifi film now, it's simply lazy writing, there was no scrap of mention of a prophecy in the original book. Why can't they be a bit more creative with plots, Nostalgia Critic was right, everything these days now involves a prophecy; sometimes it works if there's a prophecy in the actual books ie Narnia, but Tim Burton's Alice in Wonderland needlessly  had a prophecy when the original had no need for it, as well as it had no logic in the world of Wonderland. James Cameron's Avatar, for example, didn't require a prophecy for the whole plot to be driven, Jake's moral and emotional journey eventually concludes him to lead the Navi against the human alien invaders, which is more fascinating and emotionally investing than if he was doing to it just because people were telling him "the prophecy says so", and yeah there's a kind of back story where a Navi is supposed to ride the largest dragon thing- Taruk Makto- whatever it's called but that takes up a minor section. Here you have the start of Peter as he becomes Peter Pan. He's Peter freaking Pan! Why should he obey what the prophecy tells him to do, he's a child, a boy who is rebellious and does what he wants! For heavens sake he cuts off the hand of his adult nemesis Hook. How can we perceive that same character earlier on to do as a prophecy tells him to do? He's his own character, it'd be far more involving to see him make the decisions and in conflict that leads him to being Peter Pan himself through the cause and effect in his choice of interaction with others. Prophecy in a film equals lazy effort to me since we are not seeing the characters themselves drive the film since the writers want the story that way with no other explanation that "it's what's in the prophecy". Don't get me wrong this trailer looks incredible, by emphasis on looks, story wise however i doubt it because of the generic fantasy story using a prophecy and thus taking away a little life from the plot and a choice of will from the characters :(

text: The 2003 version of Peter Pan was THE BEST!  This movie cannot compare.  What is the point to making another adaptation (and a lame one at that). What makes this movie worse is that they portray it as a prequel...seriously if a production is going to make a prequel, at least make it somewhat accurate to J. Barrie's original story! And its not even creative! This is like a knock off Sci-fi movie Neverland, where Peter and Hook were friends. But hell at least that version had a NATIVE AMERICAN Tiger Lily and Peter Pan kept his clever and fun personality. And then how did Peter Pan get to neverland? Tinkerbell was the reason he could fly there!  What is up with these crappy retellings these days? The trend has to stop because it kills originality.  This movie is going to be the worse I've seen of the Peter Pan series. I hated Hook...but at least hook respected the original story.    I am going to see it...I've seen every movie based off of Peter Pan because I'm a die hard fan.  But I have a feeling I'm going to like this movie the least.

text: Disappointing movie. Saw it on Friday. Hugh Jackman is the only good actor in the film. The boy playing pan is whiny and effete, less reminiscent of a WW2 orphan and more of a modern whiny entitled brat. He's also irrelevant to the story or action of the movie for more than half of it.   Natives were garish and seemed to be as "culturally diverse" as possible for no real reason.  The worst part is that the movie makes constant references and callbacks to Hook, a far superior film, that only serves to remind you that you could have saved $20-30 and watched Hook again from the comfort of your own couch.  I give this movie 1 out of 5 Dustin Hoffmans, and 0 out of 5 Robin Williams.

text: This is for all of those who are asking why Tiger Lily is white. If you've read the imdb, you'd know why.   The casting of the Caucasian actress Rooney Mara as the Native American character of Tiger Lily led to an online petition that urged Warner Bros to stop casting Caucasian actors to play people of color. The casting was accused of whitewashing and the petition originally hoped for 5000 signatures. However, more than 20,000 signatures have supported the accusation.

Why couldn't they choose real life locations, there are so many astonishing places all over the world, nature parks etc. It is also tonally very strange. text: Many of us did grow up on the original and it is a story that will always be Loved by many generations. JM B created Peter Pan for his Lost boy childhood. And in doing so he did help and heal many other rejected lost children's childhoods. There has been many different kinds and remakes of Pan but they all are for the one main reason. Peter Pan the boy of 12 who lives forever and can fly. This one was flopped by many in the States and the UK by those who wanted this the same as the original animation all time family classic. They did not see know understand what us many rejected childhoods did. In this we find out who Peters parents are and how and why he can fly without fairies dust. This had more to it and JM Barrie would be very proud of this one because it had more in it. This was different but brilliant and did show us how Peter Pan came to be. This will go on like the animation classic.

text: The 2003 version of Peter Pan was THE BEST!  This movie cannot compare.  What is the point to making another adaptation (and a lame one at that). What makes this movie worse is that they portray it as a prequel...seriously if a production is going to make a prequel, at least make it somewhat accurate to J. Barrie's original story! And its not even creative! This is like a knock off Sci-fi movie Neverland, where Peter and Hook were friends. But hell at least that version had a NATIVE AMERICAN Tiger Lily and Peter Pan kept his clever and fun personality. And then how did Peter Pan get to neverland? Tinkerbell was the reason he could fly there!  What is up with these crappy retellings these days? The trend has to stop because it kills originality.  This movie is going to be the worse I've seen of the Peter Pan series. I hated Hook...but at least hook respected the original story.    I am going to see it...I've seen every movie based off of Peter Pan because I'm a die hard fan.  But I have a feeling I'm going to like this movie the least.

text: Blackbeard;  Hugh Jackman; I was captivated.  The camera hung on his every word when he described the fairytale of the child whom could fly and would come to kill him; the last words when the tears came to his eyes.  Every word, Hugh was right in the front of the camera and Wright did capture him amazingly.  If people wanted the Disney version of Pan; then yeeshka go rent it.  I watched this movie and was enthralled from beginning to end but most importantly; I think this was Hugh Jackman's star performance!  Perhaps people should see a Trailer beforehand because if they wanted Disney's version then why bother?  Wright never fails to capture things differently and this was a spectacle but moreover, it was a huge enthralling story.  I remember when he shot "Lizzy in Pride and Prejudice cleaning her palate at the dinner table with her finger; (absolutely never); completely wrong in the whole premise of Elizabeth but hey he's just going off of the Screen Writers story.  I though this was award effort by Jackman.  The best!

text: (watched on TV today this is my review)  Disastrous such disconnection from the original JM Barrie masterpiece it is quiet bewildering why the film is not integral to being the prequel to the original story and why all the characters look like they're from different films. Captain Hook looks like he is Indiana Jones and tigerlily looks like she is from Glastonbury Festival.   the best interpretations of JM Barry's masterpiece are the Disney Peter Pan the film Hook which is in my opinion a masterpiece starring Dustin Hoffman Robin Williams Julia Roberts Maggie Smith and Bob Hoskins   The previous Peter Pan film was actually pretty good and pretty accurate in alignment to the original stories.  unless the director is planning on making a sequel to the pan movie than this has no merit as being known as the prequel.   a completely irrelevant film that introduces characters like Blackbeard that has no relevance to Peter Pan whatsoever and doesn't do much to explain the relationship between Peter and Captain Hook.   overall the film is a jumbled conceptual nightmare that doesn't give prevalence or explanation to the story of Peter Pan it's simply fuses together different concepts like Indiana Jones (Captain Hook) Blackbeard etc and tries to make a cohesive story which it certainly doesn't.  the film doesn't explore the core principles of Peter Pan ie not growing up, lost boys, Pan vs Hook, Wendy etc    Please reply back to this with your opinions
